[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(13) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "The gate of the valley,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " opening on Hinnom, to the south of the city. Nehemiah passed by “the dragon well,” nowhere else mentioned, and not now to be traced, and surveyed the ruins from the “dung port,” whence offal was taken to the valley of Hinnom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Nehemiah 2:13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Nehemiah 2:13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I went out by night — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The footmen who accompanied him directing and leading him in the way. His design was to go around the city, to observe the compass and condition of the walls and gates, that he might make sufficient provisions for the work. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "By the gate of the valley — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of which see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Even before the dragon-well — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A fountain of water so called, either from some figure of a dragon or serpent which was by it, or from some living dragon which had taken up its abode there when the city was desolate. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "To the dung-port — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Through which they used to carry the dung out of the city.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "2:9-18 When Nehemiah had considered the matter, he told the Jews that God had put it into his heart to build the wall of Jerusalem. He does not undertake to do it without them. By stirring up ourselves and one another to that which is good, we strengthen ourselves and one another for it. We are weak in our duty, when we are cold and careless.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The gate of the valley - A gate opening on the valley of Hinnom, which skirted Jerusalem to the west and south. The exact position is uncertain; as is also that of \"the dragon well.\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The dung port - The gate by which offal and excrements were conveyed out of the city, and placed eastward of the valley-gate. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The dung port - The gate by which offal and excrements were conveyed out of the city, and placed eastward of the valley-gate. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "13-15. I went out by night by the gate of the valley—that is, the Jaffa gate, near the tower of Hippicus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "even before the dragon well—that is, fountain on the opposite side of the valley.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and to the dung port—the gate on the east of the city, through which there ran a common sewer to the brook Kedron and the valley of Hinnom.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
