  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And I went out by night, by the gate of the valley,.... Where that formerly stood, for the gates had been burnt, and were not as yet rebuilt; this was the gate that led to the valley of Jehoshaphat, according to some; or rather to the valley of dead bodies, through which the brook Kidron ran, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 26:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is the gate through which Christ went to Calvary; it led to Shiloh, Bethhoron, and Golan: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "even before the dragon well; so called from its winding about, just as a crooked winding river is called serpentine; though some think here stood an image of a dragon, either in wood, or stone, or brass, out of the mouth of which the water flowed from the well; and others, that since the desolations of Jerusalem, serpents or dragons had their abode here: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and to the dung port; by which they used to carry the dung out of the city, and by which they went to Joppa, the sea, and all the western parts: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and viewed the walls of Jerusalem: in what condition they were, what was necessary to be wholly taken down, and where to begin to build: it must have been a moonlight night or he could not have taken a view; for to have carried torches or lamps with them would have discovered them: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and the gates thereof were consumed with fire; nothing of them remained. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and the gates thereof were consumed with fire; nothing of them remained. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Geneva Study Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cverse2",
        "text": "And I went out by night by the gate of the valley, even before the dragon well, and to the dung port, and viewed the walls of Jerusalem, which were broken down, and the gates thereof were consumed with fire.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "by the gate of the valley",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "by the valley gate.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The R.V. rendering is preferable, showing that Nehemiah is not merely defining the position of the gate but is referring to it by its recognised name.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The valley-gate is mentioned again in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The king Uzziah according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 26:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " had fortified this gate with towers. We may safely identify this gate as the chief gate in the western wall of Jerusalem, and as thus corresponding to the modern Jaffa Gate, although very possibly not standing at precisely the same spot. There were two well-known valleys outside the walls of Jerusalem, (1) the ‘valley’ or ‘ravine’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "gai",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of Hinnom or ‘the son of Hinnom,’ i.e. Gehenna, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 18:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 28:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 33:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 11:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 7:31-32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; (2) the ‘valley’ or ‘brook’ or ‘watercourse’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "nakhal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of Kedron. In the present verse the word for ‘valley’ is ‘",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "gai",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",’ and this fact coupled with the general topographical description here and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", shows that ‘the valley-gate’ was the western gate leading out into the ravine of Hinnom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Recent investigations, however, have given rise to the supposition that pre-exilic Jerusalem was much smaller in circuit and that the western wall passed down the valley of the Tyropoeon. If so, ‘the valley-gate’ would be the gate opening into the Tyropoeon, which in those days was a considerable ravine but has since become almost completely choked with accumulations of ruin. According to this view the Tyropoeon is to be identified with the Valley of the Son of Hinnom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "even before the dragon well",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "even towards the dragon’s well.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The LXX. misreading the less common word in the Hebrew for ‘dragon,’ renders ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καὶ πρὸς στὸμα πηγῆς τῶν συκῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The name is doubtless connected with some sanctuary at this fountain in prehistoric times, when ‘living water’ was associated with the worship of a deity often represented by a ‘dragon.’ Prof. Robertson Smith (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Religion of the Semites",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", pp. 156, 157) calls attention to ‘the connection of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "jinns",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the form of dragons or serpents with sacred or healing springs’ … ‘The river of Coele-Syria, the Orontes, was carved out, according to local tradition, by a great dragon, which disappeared in the earth at its source.’ The explanation that the well was so called ‘because some curious large watersnake or crocodile was kept in it in Nehemiah’s time’ may be disregarded as fanciful and improbable.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The identification of the well is uncertain. By some it has been identified with ‘En-Rogel,’ near ‘the serpent’s stone,’ the stone of Zoheleth (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 2:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". By others it has been identified with ‘the fountain of Gihon’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Neither of these suggestions suits the present verse, from which we gather that ‘the dragon fountain stood on the W. or S.W. wall of the city.’ If it was a spring in the Tyropoeon Valley, it has long since been choked up. ‘The rock-hewn conduit which has been found running along the bed of the Tyropoeon Valley’ (Sir Chas. Wilson’s ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jerusalem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 113, 1889) may very well have conducted the water from such a spring. The ‘serpent,’ or Mamilla Pool, lay at the N. end of the modern Hinnom Valley (Joseph. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Bell. Jud.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " v. 3. 2).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "dung port",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "dung gate.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The A.V. probably introduced the rendering ‘port’ as an intentional variation. For ‘port’ as the old English word for ‘gate,’ compare in the Prayer-book Version ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 9:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ‘within the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ports",
        "children": []
